<DOC><DOCNO> AP890427-0005 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2352EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0756 04-27 0652</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,0663</SECOND><HEAD>Winter Lingers in the Rockies</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with twisters in Iowa, Nebraska;picks up 3rd graf pvs: `Heavy snow ...</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A spring snowstorm swept across the Rockies on Thursday, dumpingup to 8 inches of heavy, wet snow in Montana, while winds and newsnow created near blizzard conditions in parts of Wyoming andtornadoes hit southern Iowa.   A twister struck the Bluffs Run greyhound racetrack in CouncilBluffs about 8 p.m. Thursday, sending one man to the hospital forstitches after he was struck by flying debris, officials said.   The tornado, which touched down in a field about 1,000 yardsfrom the track, ripped siding from the building, downed trees anddamaged some cars with wind-blown debris, officials said. The dograces were delayed about 15 minutes.   Another tornado was reported on the ground in southern Omaha,Neb., about 7:40 p.m. and funnel clouds were sighted over thecentral part of the city as well as near Papillion and 20 mileswest of Omaha, the weather service said.   There were no immediate reports of injury, streets flooded inOmaha and golf-ball sized hail caused extensive damage to many carsafter a day of record high temperatures in Nebraska and in theSouth.   Heavy snow warnings were posted through Friday over the northernmountains of Wyoming, with up to a foot of snowfall expected bylate Friday in the Laramie Range.   Near Cheyenne, Wyo., about 6 inches of new snow combined withstrong and gusty winds to create near blizzard conditions Thursdaymorning.   In south-central Montana, 8 inches of snow fell on Red Lodge, aski resort community. Great Falls, Cut Bank, Helena, Butte, Bozemanand Livingston all had accumulations of 2 to 4 inches.   ``We've got big, white flat flakes coming down here, about thesize of a quarter,'' said Phil Kumm in Great Falls, Mont.   Elsewhere, afternoon showers and thunderstorms extended Thursdayalong the northern coast of North Carolina, as well as fromsouthwestern West Virginia into eastern Kentucky. Showers werescattered over west-central Minnesota, as well as from southwesternSouth Dakota across western Nebraska and eastern Colorado andeastern Idaho.   High-temperature records for the date were set in seven citiesand tied in two.   Grand Island, Neb., broke its record of 87 set in 1901 with andafternoon high of 88. Other records included Apalachicola, Fla.,high of 86, breaking its record of 84 set in 1948; in Lincoln,Neb., (92, 91 set in 1896); Nashville, Tenn., (90, 89 set 1987);Omaha, Neb., (88, 87 in 1981); Paducah, Ky., (89, 87 in 1987).Charleston, S.C., tied its record of 93, set in 1986 and St. Louis,Mo., tied its record of 89, set 1956.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 31degrees at Miles City, Mont., to 93 degrees at Charleston, S.C. Thenation's low Thursday was 16 degrees at Truckee, Calif.   The national forecast for Friday called for showers andthunderstorms from the Ohio Valley across southern lower Michigan,Wisconsin and Illinois, from much of Missouri across southwestMinnesota; the northern Plains, and from Montana across northernColorado and Idaho; rain becoming snow in the higher elevations ofthe northern and central Rockies; and showers scattered throughnortheast Texas.   High temperatures were forecast in the 30s from western SouthDakota across central Wyoming; in the 40s and 50s from New Englandacross the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northernPlains; northwest Nebraska, and the Rockies; the 60s and 70s fromsouthern New York across Virginia, West Virginia, Ohio, Indiana,northern Illinois, Iowa, the central Plains, western Oklahoma, theOklahoma-Texas panhandles, and the Pacific Coast; in the 90s fromsoutheastern South Carolina across much of Georgia and northernFlorida, as well as southwest Arizona into southeast California;and in the 80s throughout the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>